import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Environment Overlays"
  description="Multi-environment configuration with shuttle.production.yml and environment-specific overrides"
  section="Configuration"
>
  <p>
    Most projects need different configuration per environment: a different server, different
    secrets file, or a different deploy strategy for staging vs production. Shuttle handles
    this with <em>environment overlays</em> — additional YAML files that are deep-merged on
    top of your base <code>shuttle.yml</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>How overlays work</h2>
  <p>
    The base config is always loaded from <code>shuttle.yml</code>. Then, if an environment
    is active, Shuttle loads <code>shuttle.&lt;env&gt;.yml</code> from the same directory and
    deep-merges it on top of the base config.
  </p>
  <p>
    Deep merge rules:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Scalar values (strings, numbers, booleans) in the overlay <strong>replace</strong> the base value.</li>
    <li>Maps (objects) are merged recursively — keys present in the overlay are updated, keys absent from the overlay are kept from the base.</li>
    <li>Arrays in the overlay <strong>replace</strong> the base array entirely (they are not concatenated).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Activating an environment</h2>
  <p>There are two ways to activate an environment:</p>

  <h3>1. Environment variable</h3>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">SHUTTLE_ENV=production shuttle deploy</code></pre>

  <h3>2. CLI flag</h3>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle deploy --env production</code></pre>
  <p>
    The <code>--env</code> flag takes precedence over the <code>SHUTTLE_ENV</code> environment
    variable. If neither is set, no overlay is loaded and only the base <code>shuttle.yml</code>
    is used.
  </p>

  <h2>File naming convention</h2>
  <p>
    The overlay file must be named <code>shuttle.&lt;env&gt;.yml</code> and placed next to your
    base <code>shuttle.yml</code>. Common examples:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>shuttle.production.yml</code></li>
    <li><code>shuttle.staging.yml</code></li>
    <li><code>shuttle.preview.yml</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Example: staging vs production</h2>

  <h3>shuttle.yml (base config)</h3>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">app: my-app
domain: staging.my-app.example.com
server: deploy@staging-server.example.com

build:
  context: .
  dockerfile: Dockerfile

deploy:
  strategy: blue-green
  timeout: 120
  retain: 3
  auto_rollback: true

services:
  web:
    port: 3000
    healthcheck:
      path: /up

accessories:
  postgres:
    preset: postgres
    env:
      POSTGRES_DB: my_app_staging
      POSTGRES_USER: my_app
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: !secret DB_PASSWORD
  mailpit:
    preset: mailpit

secrets:
  file: .shuttle.staging.secrets

proxy:
  driver: caddy
  ssl: true</code></pre>

  <h3>shuttle.production.yml (production overlay)</h3>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml"># Only specify what differs from the base config.
# Everything not listed here inherits from shuttle.yml.

domain: my-app.example.com
server: deploy@203.0.113.10

deploy:
  retain: 10                  # keep more history in production

accessories:
  postgres:
    env:
      POSTGRES_DB: my_app_production  # different database name

  # Remove mailpit in production — override with null or omit
  # mailpit is simply absent from this overlay, so it IS present (inherited).
  # To remove an accessory in production, set it to null explicitly:
  mailpit: ~

env:
  clear:
    APP_ENV: production

secrets:
  file: .shuttle.production.secrets  # separate secrets file per environment</code></pre>

  <h3>Deploying to production</h3>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">SHUTTLE_ENV=production shuttle deploy
# or
shuttle deploy --env production</code></pre>

  <h2>Separate secrets per environment</h2>
  <p>
    It is best practice to maintain a separate encrypted secrets file for each environment.
    This way staging secrets cannot accidentally be used in production and vice versa.
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash"># Set a production secret (reads from shuttle.production.yml to find the secrets file)
SHUTTLE_ENV=production shuttle secrets set APP_KEY "base64:..."
SHUTTLE_ENV=production shuttle secrets set DB_PASSWORD "prod-password"

# Push secrets to production server
SHUTTLE_ENV=production shuttle secrets push</code></pre>

  <h2>Using overlays in CI/CD</h2>
  <p>
    In a GitHub Actions workflow, set <code>SHUTTLE_ENV</code> as an environment variable:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">- name: Deploy to production
  env:
    SHUTTLE_ENV: production
    SHUTTLE_LICENSE_KEY: $&#123;&#123; secrets.SHUTTLE_LICENSE_KEY &#125;&#125;
  run: shuttle deploy</code></pre>

  <h2>What to put in overlays vs base config</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Config</th>
        <th>Where to put it</th>
        <th>Reason</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Build configuration</td>
        <td>Base <code>shuttle.yml</code></td>
        <td>Same image built for all environments</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Service definitions</td>
        <td>Base <code>shuttle.yml</code></td>
        <td>Same services across environments</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Server address</td>
        <td>Overlay</td>
        <td>Different VPS per environment</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Domain</td>
        <td>Overlay</td>
        <td>Different subdomain per environment</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Secrets file path</td>
        <td>Overlay</td>
        <td>Separate encrypted secrets per environment</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Retain count</td>
        <td>Overlay</td>
        <td>Production may warrant more history</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Accessory env (DB name, user)</td>
        <td>Overlay</td>
        <td>Separate databases per environment</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Committing overlay files</h2>
  <p>
    Overlay files are safe to commit to your repository. They contain no secrets — all
    sensitive values use the <code>!secret</code> tag which references the encrypted secrets
    file. The encrypted secrets files themselves are also safe to commit (AES-256-GCM encrypted).
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">git add shuttle.yml shuttle.staging.yml shuttle.production.yml
git add .shuttle.staging.secrets .shuttle.production.secrets
git commit -m "chore: add shuttle configuration"</code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
